a:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Snapdragon X2 Elite outscores Intel’s Panther Lake in early benchmarks"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"ARM’s Windows laptop push gains hard performance proof"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Synthetic wins ≠ real-world dominance—yet"}]]}]]}]}]
b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Qualcomm just dropped a ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.geekbench.com","children":"Geekbench"}]," scorecard that reads like a taunt to Intel: its upcoming ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Snapdragon X2 Elite Extreme"}]," chip allegedly outmuscles Intel’s flagship ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Core Ultra X9 388H"}],"—the crown jewel of its Panther Lake lineup—by ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.windowscentral.com/software-apps/windows-11/qualcomm-snapdragon-x2-elite-extreme-beats-intel-core-ultra-x9-388h-in-early-benchmarks","children":"margins"}]," that should make x86 engineers sweat. On paper, this is ARM’s loudest declaration yet that Windows laptops don’t need Intel’s architecture to flex. But let’s be clear: ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"synthetic benchmarks are the opening act, not the headliner."}],"\nThe numbers are eye-catching. The Snapdragon X2 Elite Extreme, built on a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"custom Oryon core"}],", reportedly hits ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"multi-core scores"}]," that leave Intel’s top-tier Panther Lake chip looking like last-gen silicon. For Qualcomm, this isn’t just about bragging rights—it’s about ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"proving ARM can handle the workloads"}]," (read: Adobe Suite, heavy multitasking, local AI inference) that kept x86 entrenched in pro laptops. Intel’s response? ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.intel.com","children":"Silence"}],", though its roadmap still bets big on ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"hybrid architectures"}]," and efficiency cores.\nHere’s the catch: Geekbench is a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"controlled sprint"}],", not a marathon. Real-world performance hinges on ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"driver maturity, thermal throttling, and—crucially—Windows on ARM’s app compatibility"}],". Remember when Apple’s M1 crushed Intel in benchmarks, only for some pro apps to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/11/m1-macbook-pro-review-fast-but-not-without-flaws/","children":"choke on Rosetta"}],"? Qualcomm’s playing the same high-stakes game, but with a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"fragmented Windows ecosystem"}]," instead of Apple’s walled garden."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/qualcomms-arm-ambush-is-intels-laptop-crown-slippi/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Geekbench loves it. But will developers, IT buyers, and your battery life agree?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Geekbench loves it. But will developers, IT buyers, and your battery life agree?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"industry map"}]," here is straightforward: Qualcomm wins if OEMs like Dell and Lenovo start shipping ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"ARM-first premium laptops"}],"—not as niche experiments, but as default recommendations. Intel loses if its ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Panther Lake efficiency gains"}]," (which are real) get drowned out by ARM’s raw scoreboard dominance. AMD? Sitting pretty, watching two giants bleed while it ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.anandtech.com/show/20950/amd-ryzen-ai-300-series-strix-point-apus-coming-july-2024","children":"polishes its Strix Point chips"}],".\nDevelopers, meanwhile, are ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"loud but divided"}],". GitHub threads on ","$L13"," spike whenever Qualcomm drops a new chip, but the pattern’s familiar: ","$L14",". Adobe’s ","$L15"," is improving, but “good enough” isn’t “optimized.” And let’s not forget ","$L16",", where Qualcomm’s presence is still a ","$L17",".\nThe ","$L18"," is where this gets interesting. Even if the X2 Elite Extreme delivers, Qualcomm’s ","$L19"," and ","$L1a"," remain unproven. Intel, for all its stumbles, still owns the ","$L1b"," and the ","$L1c"," that keeps businesses buying Core i7s by the pallet. ARM’s moment isn’t about beating Intel in a benchmark—it’s about ","$L1d"]}]]}]
